<font color="#FF0000">A FEW COMMENTS</font><br>
<tt>Mon Jun 30 16:44:25 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To Cook,<br>
You make some interesting points, some of which I agree with, some I don't agree with.  Here are some of my thoughts:<br><br>
 In regards to the rules of engagement-America had some poor ones.  Explain to me when it is acceptable to shoot someone that is running away (even when they are unarmed).  I understand they could be VC/NVA, but I'll tell you this, if I saw a armed patrol approaching, I would DI DI too!!  Horrible fire discipline was one our major problems.  I understand that in war it is shoot first, ask questions later and had I been in Vietnam, I suppose the situation would dictate that I follow that rule.  No offense to the men who handled the war on the day to day basis, I have the deepest respect for all Nam vets, My gripe is with the persons or circumstances that allow the this type of engagement to occur.  The enemy had a rule of engagement, I suggest you read Inside the VC/NVA by Michael Lanning or the Navy/Marine Corp manual &quot;Professional Knowledge&quot; NAVMC 2614 from 1967, which describes the tactics of our enemy.  They were not simple farmers, but a well organized and trained force.<br><br>
As for innocent victims in war, your right it happens in every war, always will!!  In Europe, the allies destroyed the French town of Caen during the D-Day battle, causing numerous casualties among civilians.  But our military must always be held to the highest standards,even if our enemy does not.   The Vietnam environment and nature of warfare played right into the hands of the VC/NVA propaganda machine.  In the future all of us need to make sure that America is never placed in a situation like Vietnam again, with no clear cut goals or enemy.<br><br>
The enemy fired first 7 out of 10 times in Vietnam, Charlie was picking the fights many times.  The war was about body counts and attrition.  That's the fundamental point.  How can you win a war like that?  Land is meaningless, who cares if you clear a village, Charlie will be back there again later.  It was a war with no goals and a enagagement system that favored the enemy.  I just don't see how we could have won unless we changed tactics and created goals.  It may be have been a tactical victory for us (the small battles), but it was certainly a strategic victory for the enemy.   <br><br>
  As for firing first while on perimeter, I took it up with my father who was a Navy Seabee (who spent time at the Army camp of Bien Hoa by the way) and he told me that firing without having a target allows the enemy to identify the location of your emplacements.  Thus on another night, you could eat a RPG or have them find your weaknesses (By the way each Seabee battalion has a Marine Gunny as a advisor for security, so I don't think security is different between branches, just different between units, leaders etc.) Also, he said that his men needed clearance to open fire, no John Wayne stuff on perimeter.  They were subject to numerous attacks, but never had they enemy break through or had to call for help.  I don't believe anyone waits to see the whites of their eyes, if you can see the whites of their eyes, then someone was not paying attention.<br><br>
In regards to TET, you are right, we won that one militarily, but the enemy won a propaganda victory. The enemy that was ready to sacrifice many more men than we were and I believe America had enough.  I'm not a military planner, but after three years of full military involvement, when the enemy throws a major offensive, it is time to review our place there.  I think mainstream America did just that,  The tenacity of their attack (foolish as it may seem at times) was enough to change opinion here in the US.  In the New York city area, where my family and I are from, TET made a lot of the blue collar middle class families in the city take notice of the war and start them to demand why and question the sacrifice.  I've had vets tell me that many people took it as a shock, during a time when many Americans thought we were making progress.  So was a military victory important or a propaganda one, war can be so confusing. <br><br>
My comments on the war are based on all I've heard and read.  Understanding Vietnam has been a passion for me for many years.  I am the son of a Vietnam Vet, so my comments are made with the deepest respect for all vets, I'm not some kind of radical anti-war nut, just someone who does not see sense or meaning in a war that caused so much pain, killed so many of our young guys and their (all Vietnamese) young guys.  Thanks for stating your opinions and sharing your views and experiences.  Talking this out is the best way for any of us to understand this (especially those of us who were born after the war-I'm 23).<br>

